\begin_layout Standard
Wind electricity is an intermittent and volatile source of energy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gibescuEstimationVariabilityPredictability2009,ummelsImpactsWindPower2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When there is no or little wind, there is not enough electricity to match
 the demand; when there is too much wind, if the electricity is not consumed
 immediately, it will be wasted.
 The Ciara storm in February 2020, which was only partially felt in Denmark,
 increased the Danish wind electricity production to 1000 Mega Watts (MW)
 above consumption, i.e.
 20% higher that is equivalent to the average demand of one million European
 citizens.
 There were reports of significant curtailments up to several thousand MW
 from other countries in the North Sea region.
 Curtailment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lewWindSolarCurtailment2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which means accepting less renewable electricity than what windfarms can
 deliver is another word for wasted resources.
 It will soon become more severe when the North Sea is hit by a technological
 storm in the form of several large wind farms that are currently evaluated,
 planned, and licensed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GlobalOffshoreRenewable"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 More importantly, since the electricity distribution is planned based on
 the unavailability of wind resources, the biomass (that is regularly switched
 to coal) power plants must always be running to compensate for the shortage
 of wind, thus emitting a large amount of carbon dioxide and other pollutants
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "meibomEnergyComesTogether2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The solution is to store electricity when production is higher than demand
 and consume it when demand is higher than production 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pedersenEnergyStorageTechnologies2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
