\begin_layout Section
Future energy need of Denmark
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denmark currently consumes around 100 kWh per person per day of energy in
 different forms.
 Eftekhari 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhariQuantifyingRoleLiquid2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 showed that this can be further categorized into 30% electricity, 30% heat,
 and 40% hydrocarbon fuel.
 Note that the hydrocarbon consumption for electricity production is not
 included in the 40% hydrocarbon fuel.
 We can assume that in the future, all the warming systems and short distance
 transport will be electrified; therefore, by assuming a realistic (yet
 conservative) coefficient of performance of 2.0 for the future warming systems,
 we can estimate a demand of 45 kWh/day electricity per person and 40 kWh/day
 liquid fuel per person.
 As for electricity production, the current plan is to quadruple the current
 electricity capacity of the wind mills in the North Sea.
 Since the capacity is not equal to the actual produced electricity (due
 to, e.g.
 technical problems, curtailment, weather conditions, etc.) we will estimate
 the intermittent electricity production of the windmills by quadrupling
 the current electricity production in Denmark that is available from Energinet.d
k website and also available as a public repository 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhariSimulkadeStorageFirst2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, including several Matlab functions for analysis and visualizations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electricity-surplus-smooth"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the electricity supply and demand from May 2021 to January 2021 (left)
 and for the same period in 2050 (right).
 We can use Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:average-energy-demand"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to integrate the data and obtain the average energy supply and demand
 over different periods of time, i.e.
 from 24 hours to nine month, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:average-energy-demand"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{E}=\frac{1}{t_{2}-t_{1}}\int_{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}E\left(t\right)dt,\label{eq:average-energy-demand}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E(t)$
\end_inset

 [MW] is the electricity supply or demand in the future and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 [s] and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 [s] represent a certain time period.
 The future energy supply and demand are estimated by using the correction
 factor extracted from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhariQuantifyingRoleLiquid2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{future}=\lambda_{i}E_{current},\quad i=s,\,d\label{eq:demand-adjust}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{d}=1.5$
\end_inset

 denotes a 50% in electricity demand 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eftekhariQuantifyingRoleLiquid2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{s}=4.0$
\end_inset

 denotes a 400% increase of windmill capacity in Denmark 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "danishenergyagencyEnergyIslands2021,dandreaSynergiesOffshoreEnergy2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that this increase will be on the offshore sector only; however, here
 we assume that the overall wind energy capacity will increase by a factor
 of four.
 The other assumption in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand-adjust"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is that the weather (more specifically, wind) in 2050 will be similar
 to the weather condition in 2020.
 The visualized energy supply and demand in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electricity-surplus-smooth"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that periodically, the wind electricity supply is higher or lower
 than the electricity demand, creating periods with electricity surplus
 and shortage, respectively.
 The alternation between surplus and shortage can occur within a few hours
 to few weeks.
 This is better visualized in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Average-electricity-supply"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that shows the average surplus and shortage for periods of 24 hours to
 8 months.
 It can be observed that after around six months, the average surplus and
 shortage reach a constant value.
 This plot unveils three critical pieces of information about the wind electrici
ty supply and demand in 2050: first, the average shortage of electricity
 is 1.6 GW, which is a large amount of power and gives an indication of the
 amount of energy that needs to be stored (although sometimes the actual
 power shortage is temporarily higher as shown later).
 The good news is that the average electricity surplus is 2.25 GW, which
 is 620 MW higher than the average electricity shortage.
 These two numbers, however, serve as a constraint for the efficiency of
 the energy storage technology, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{storage}>\frac{\text{Average shortage}}{\text{Average surplus}}=0.72.
\]

\end_inset

This means that the efficiency of the storage technology must be higher
 than 72%.
